AEHEVNT: Multifocal infiltrating mixed lobular and ductal carcinoma, left breast
AEHCOMM: Participant’s mammogram on 07/12/2017 showed a small 6 MM speculated density in the upper outer quadrant of the left breast. She had a left lateral biopsy on her breast on 07/20/2017 and was diagnosed with recurrent invasive carcinoma, ER/PR positive and HER-2 negative by FISH. She was treated surgically with left breast wide local excision on 08/01/2017. Pathology showed multifocal infiltrating mixed lobular (85%) and ductal (15%) carcinoma, Nottingham Grade 3 (score 2 for tubule formation, 3 for nuclear atypia, and 3 for mitosis). DCIS is present. No necrosis of the invasive carcinoma was identified and it measured 2.6 X 2.6 X 3.0 CM. The participant had a left breast re-excision on 08/22/2017 which showed two foci of residual invasive mixed mammary carcinoma (largest focus measuring 12 MM) with 1 MM focal positive margin. Her oncologist prescribed her Anastrozole 1mg QD PO. More oncology records have been requested.

Participant was observed to have seizure-like activity while at her nursing home and was taken to UK ER for evaluation. She was admitted and subsequently had another incident of seizure-like activity. Participant had been tapering off chronic use of lorazepam per discharge instruction from prior hospitalization on 08 Feb 2018. Last dose of lorazepam had been on 24 Feb 2018. She had no prior history of seizure activity. ED general note dated 24 Feb 2018 stated "Given the lack of trauma and negative workup for metabolic causes of seizures, the most likely cause was benzodiazepine withdrawal seizures given the cessation of Ativan." Participant was admitted 25 Feb - 28 Feb 2018, during which time she was followed by Internal Medicine with consults by Neurology, Pharmacy, OT/PT, Nutrition. EEG results were suggestive of mild diffuse encephalopathy. MRI showed no acute finding. Neurology recommended resuming Ativan 0.5mg QAM and 1mg QPM until follow up with Dr. Jicha/Dr. Smith on 08 Mar 2018. Participant was discharged on 28 Feb 2018 and returned to nursing home.

Patient went to the doctor on 9/17/2018 to have robotic laparoscopic colon resection. Patient had a fever and elevated WBC. It was determined he had an abscessed diverticulum with perforation. The surgery was canceled that day and rescheduled for 9/24/2018. He was treated with IV Zosyn and sent home with Levaquin and flagyl PO. Subject was asked to return in one week for the surgery. He returned to the hospital on 9/24/18 and at that time, the laparascopic colon resection was done, and he was admitted to Ephraim McDowell hospital for 7 days post operatively.
AEOTHERHX: SV 10/17/18: Patient has a history of diverticulitus. He had a perforation in January 2018 that was treated with IV and oral antibiotics. He had another episode in August 2018 at which time he had a small abscess and a micro perforation in the sigmoid colon. Both times he recovered with IV and oral antibiotics. He was scheduled for a robotic laparoscopic colon resection on 9/17/2018 but the surgery was canceled that day for an acute exacerbation of his diverticulitus. He was treated with IV Zosyn while at the hospital and sent home that evening with PO Flagyl and Levaquin. He returned one week later on 9/24/18 for the laparoscopic colon resection and was admitted to Ephraim McDowell Medical Center post operatively. He developed a post-operative ileus which was treated and resolved with NG tube decompression and time. He was in the hospital from 9/24/2018 to 9/30/2018. Patient was discharged to home on 9/30/2018 and was given Tramadol 50 mg tablets PO to be taken Q4 for pain.

Participant complained of intermittent, mild back pain beginning approximately 1 day post lumbar puncture. The pain was worsened when pressing on it or laying on her back when on a hard surface (like the floor after yoga). The pain radiated bilaterally across her back from the site of LP when present. She did not take anything to relieve the pain. It resolved spontaneously after 15 days (on 8/9/18)

Subject was finishing up a workout when he developed a slight "twinge" in the (L) side of his head. This progressed to include "tingling" sensation to (R) check, lips, (R) arm + hand, especially the (R) pinky and ring fingers. Presented to ER Easton Hospital. CT done immediately and it was clear. MRI clear. Admitted overnight. Symptoms resolved within ~8hrs of initial onset. He reports having a little less mental clarity for a couple days after the event. He gave an example of talking to his sister on the phone, and he did not recall this until his wife told him. The event happened on a Thursday morning and by Sunday morning he was completely back to normal. Since this event he has been commenced on a statin, his Losartan was increased and he was also commenced on Aspirin 81mg QD.
Patient reports bilateral lower leg cramps beginning approximately 2/16/18. Prescribed potassium chloride and symptoms resolved in a week.

Participant reported to study coordinator on 9/10/2018 that he had experienced a mild headache following Tau PET Scan on 9/6/2018 in the early afternoon. He specified that the discomfort originated from the "back of [his] head" rather than between the eyes or on a particular side of the head, as is typical of his headaches. He took Tylenol (500 mg x 2 pills) the evening of 9/6/2018, which made his headache go away. ?He did not report dizziness, nausea, confusion or imbalance -- he explained he has been feeling normal since taking the Tylenol and did not have further complaints.

Patient has a history of vertigo (and tinnitus) and after having her MIR brain scan symptom of both vertigo and tinnitus were worsened. ENT specialist prescribed medicine and patient did not take, hence it reoccurred later (feels transient vertigo and position changes).
